{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_50","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"rg -n -U 'name: obsolete [\"'^'\"\\\\n]+\\\\n(?:.*\\\\n){0,12}created_by:' src/ontology/go-edit.obo | sed -n '1,80p'\"","aggregated_output":"7209:name: obsolete tRNA exon ligation utilizing ATP as source of linkage phosphate\n7210:namespace: biological_process\n7211:def: \"OBSOLETE. A tRNA exon ligation process in which the splice junction phosphate is derived from exogenous ATP. This type of ligation to rejoin the 5' and 3' exons of a tRNA is observed in vertebrate species.\" [GOC:krc, PMID:17786051]\n7212:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term is a molecular functions.\n7213:property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27438\" xsd:anyURI\n7214:is_obsolete: true\n7215:created_by: krc\n7220:name: obsolete tRNA exon ligation utilizing GTP as source of linkage phosphate\n7221:namespace: biological_process\n7222:def: \"OBSOLETE. A tRNA exon ligation process in which the splice junction phosphate is derived from exogenous GTP. This type of ligation to rejoin the 5' and 3' exons of a tRNA is observed in the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae where the ligation reaction also produces a 2'-phosphate at the splice junction which is subsequently removed as part of the ligation process.\" [GOC:krc, PMID:18217203, PMID:9299409]\n7223:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term is a molecular function\n7224:property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27438\" xsd:anyURI\n7225:is_obsolete: true\n7226:consider: GO:0000968\n7227:created_by: krc\n7232:name: obsolete tRNA exon ligation utilizing 2',3' cyclic phosphate of 5'-exon as source of linkage phosphate\n7233:namespace: biological_process\n7234:def: \"OBSOLETE. A tRNA exon ligation process in which the splice junction phosphate is derived from the 2',3' cyclic phosphate at the 3'-end of the 5'-exon. This type of ligation to rejoin the 5' and 3' exons of a tRNA is observed in wheat, Chlamydomonas, and vertebrate species including humans.\" [GOC:krc, PMID:17786051, PMID:18217203, PMID:9299409]\n7235:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term is a molecular function.\n7236:property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27438\" xsd:anyURI\n7237:is_obsolete: true\n7238:consider: GO:0000968\n7239:created_by: krc\n7418:name: obsolete transcription factor activity, protein binding\n7419:namespace: molecular_function\n7420:def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to a protein or protein complex, to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7421:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this concept is partly covered by other concepts in the ontology and usage has been inconsistent.\n7422:synonym: \"protein binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7423:synonym: \"transcription factor activity\" BROAD []\n7424:property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/16053\" xsd:anyURI\n7425:is_obsolete: true\n7426:consider: GO:0005515\n7427:consider: GO:0140110\n7428:created_by: krc\n7433:name: obsolete transcription factor activity, transcription factor binding\n7434:namespace: molecular_function\n7435:def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to a specific transcription factor, which may be a single protein or a complex, in order to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7436:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this concept is partly covered by other concepts in the ontology and usage has been inconsistent.\n7437:synonym: \"transcription factor binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7438:property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/16053\" xsd:anyURI\n7439:is_obsolete: true\n7440:consider: GO:0008134\n7441:consider: GO:0140110\n7442:created_by: krc\n7447:name: obsolete transcription factor activity, core RNA polymerase binding\n7448:namespace: molecular_function\n7449:def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to an RNA polymerase in order to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7450:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this concept is partly covered by other concepts in the ontology and usage has been inconsistent.\n7451:synonym: \"core RNA polymerase binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7452:property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/16053\" xsd:anyURI\n7453:is_obsolete: true\n7454:consider: GO:0043175\n7455:consider: GO:0140110\n7456:created_by: krc\n7461:name: obsolete transcription factor activity, core RNA polymerase II binding\n7462:namespace: molecular_function\n7463:def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to an RNA polymerase II (Pol II) complex, typically composed of twelve subunits, in order to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7464:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this concept is partly covered by other concepts in the ontology and usage has been inconsistent.\n7465:synonym: \"core RNA polymerase II binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7466:property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/16053\" xsd:anyURI\n7467:is_obsolete: true\n7468:consider: GO:0000993\n7469:consider: GO:0140110\n7470:created_by: krc\n7615:name: obsolete transcription factor activity, RNA polymerase III transcription factor binding\n7616:namespace: molecular_function\n7617:def: \"OBSOLETE. Binding to an RNA polymerase III transcription factor, which may be a single protein or a complex, in order to modulate transcription. A protein binding transcription factor may or may not also interact with the template nucleic acid (either DNA or RNA) as well.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7618:comment: This term was obsoleted because it represents two separate functions. The corresponding 'binding' term should be used in combination with a transcription regulator activity child.\n7619:synonym: \"RNA polymerase III transcription factor binding transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7620:is_obsolete: true\n7621:created_by: krc\n7626:name: obsolete RNA polymerase II sequence-specific DNA-binding transcription factor recruiting activity\n7627:namespace: molecular_function\n7628:def: \"OBSOLETE. The function of binding to a specific DNA sequence and recruiting another transcription factor to the DNA in order to modulate transcription. The recruited factor may bind DNA directly, or may be colocalized via protein-protein interactions.\" [GOC:txnOH]\n7629:comment: This term was obsoleted because it was not clearly defined.\n7630:synonym: \"sequence-specific DNA binding transcription factor recruiting transcription factor activity\" EXACT []\n7631:synonym: \"transcription factor activity, sequence-specific DNA binding transcription factor recruiting\" EXACT []\n7632:synonym: \"transcription factor activity, sequence-specific DNA-binding transcription factor recruiting\" RELATED []\n7633:property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31456\" xsd:anyURI\n7634:is_obsolete: true\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
